The paper focuses on the MapReduce framework, which is commonly used in distributed and parallel computation. This suggests that the paper may belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) or Database (cs.DB) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper presents upper and lower bounds on the parallel I/O-complexity, which suggests that it may also belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) or Computational Complexity (cs.CC) sub-categories. Finally, the paper discusses the functionality of MapReduce in the parallel external memory model, which further supports its potential categorization under cs.DS or cs.DB.
